Good afternoon, and welcome back to the Griddle, a menu of fortified items for the busy person's media diet. Retailers are going to unprecedented lengths to make sure the Christmas season is as productive as it can be. Something's working: The National Retailers Federation projects a 3.8 percent increase in sales over last year. Some stores are extending their hours, giving customers an opportunity to engage in what might be called endurance shopping. Toys 'R' Us is keeping almost all of its 600 U.S. stores open for 112 straight hours. Some Macy's stores are going 83 hours without turning deadbolts, Matt Townsend of Bloomberg News reported today. Almost a  third  of shoppers still had holiday shopping to do this week. They may need something to read. Here's the Best of Bloomberg Sustainability from this week: Fair Trade Proving Anything But to Farmers in $6 Billion Market Victoria’s Secret Revealed in Child Picking Burkina Faso Cotton   Foxconn Hopes to Replicate iPhone Manufacturing Success in Solar Bad Roads Holding up More than Traffic in  India First Solar Never so Cheap in Takeover Boon for Energy BP Solar Business Exit Counters Trend by Google, Buffett, Total Record Coal Deals Whittle Targets as Prices Climb Shale Boom Heralds Fifth Year of Gas Declines Cornell’s $2 Billion Campus Fuels N.Y.C. Search for Tech Jobs Quake, Tornadoes, Debt Crisis Made 2011 Relentless Must We Really Turn off All Portable Electronic Devices?: View